\begin_layout Abstract
The dynamics of an electronic system interacting with an electromagnetic
 field is investigated within mixed quantum-classical theory.
 Beyond the classical path approximation (where we ignore all feedback from
 the electronic system on the photon field), we consider all electron–photon
 interactions explicitly according to Ehrenfest (i.e.
 mean–field) dynamics with coupled Maxwell–Liouville equations.
 Because Ehrenfest dynamics cannot capture certain quantum features of the
 photon filed correctly, we propose a new 
\emph on
Ehrenfest+R
\emph default
 method that can recover (by construction) spontaneous emission while also
 distinguishing between electromagnetic fluctuations and coherent emission.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
a new semiclassical propagation scheme of coupled electron-radiation dynamics
 incorporating complementary quantum transitions to account for quantum
 effects that are missed in the standard Ehrenfest dynamics.
 We demonstrate the power of Ehrenfest+R dynamics by simulation of spontaneous
 emission.
 The method can recover the Fermi's golden rule rate at the same cost of
 Ehrenfest dynamics, and reveal a semiclassical picture of the incoherent
 and coherent emissions for one- and three-dimensional systems.
 
