\end_layout

\end_inset

In particular, the most natural approach for electron–radiation dynamics
 is the Ehrenfest method, combining the quantum Liouville equation with
 classical electrodynamics in a mean-field manner, given the lack of a time-scal
e separation between electronic and EM dynamics.
 Nevertheless, Ehrenfest dynamics are known to suffer from several drawbacks.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
detail balance
\end_layout

\end_inset

First, it is well-known that, for electron–nuclei dynamics, Ehrenfest dynamics
 do not satisfy detailed balance.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parandekar_detailed_2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 This drawback will usually lead to incorrect electronic populations at
 long times.
 The failure to maintain detailed balance leads to anomalous energy flow
 (that can even sometimes violate the second law of thermodynamics at equilibriu
m.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jain_vibrational_2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) For electron–radiation dynamics, this problem may not be fatal since the
 absorption and emission of a radiation field may be considered relatively
 fast compared to electron–nuclei dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
partially correct
\end_layout

\end_inset

Apart from any concerns about detail balance, Ehrenfest dynamics has other
 deficiencies regarding various quantum effects, especially spontaneous
 and stimulated emission.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li_mixed_2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 For example, consider a situation where the electronic system has zero
 average current initially and exists within a vacuum environment without
 external fields; if the electronic state is excited, one expects spontaneous
 emission to occur.
 However, according to Ehrenfest dynamics, the electron–radiation coupling
 will remain zero always, so that Ehrenfest dynamics will not predict any
 spontaneous emission.
 
