Before studying spontaneous emission in detail, one must choose a Hamiltonian
 and a gauge for QED calculations.
 Because we believe the method naturally offers a semiclassical interpretation,
 we will work with the Power-Zienau-Woolley Hamiltonian
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "power_coulomb_1959,atkins_interaction_1970,cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 in the Coulomb gauge (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}_{\parallel}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{A}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 )
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{\text{PZW}}=\widehat{H}_{s}+\widehat{H}_{R}+\widehat{H}_{\text{int}}\label{eq:Power-Zienau-Woolley}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{R}=\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left\{ \frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\left(\mathbf{\nabla}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right)^{2}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{\text{int}}=-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+\frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left|\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right|^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{\text{int}}=-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the vector potential of the EM field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the transverse field displacement, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\epsilon_{0}\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian of the matter system and will be specified below.
 Note that the Power-Zienau-Woolley Hamiltonian is rigorously equivalent
 to the more standard 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

