\begin_layout Subsection
Semiclassical Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define a semiclassical Hamiltonian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}_{\text{SC}}$
\end_inset

 that approximates Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Power-Zienau-Woolley"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mukamel_principles_1999"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}\widehat{H}_{\text{SC}}= & \widehat{H}_{s}-\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\\
 & +\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left\{ \frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)^{2}\right\} .
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, we treat the EM field operators as classical electrodynamics parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\rightarrow\mathbf{D}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\epsilon_{0}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)+\mathbf{P}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\nabla}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\rightarrow\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

, so that we can commute 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}$
\end_inset

 in the coupling term.
 Note that the average polarization is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\text{Tr}_{s}\left\{ \widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 From the semiclassical Hamiltonian, we can extract an electronic Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}^{\text{el}}\left(\mathbf{E}\right)=\widehat{H}_{s}-\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).\label{eq:electronic_Hamiltonian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which depends only parametrically on the EM field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ehrenfest dynamics 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ehrenfest anstaz
\end_layout

\end_inset

Within Ehrenfest dynamics, the electronic system is described by the electronic
 density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 while the EM field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

, are propagated by classical electrodynamics.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
density matrix - Liouville
\end_layout

\end_inset

The electronic density matrix evolves according to the Liouville equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\widehat{H}^{\mathrm{el}}\left(\mathbf{E}\right),\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\right].\label{eq:liouville_rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
EM field - Maxwell
\end_layout

\end_inset

The EM field is governed by Maxwell's equation for classical electrodynamics
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & -\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_BE}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & c^{2}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\mathbf{J}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_EB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the average current is generated by the average polarization of the
 electronic system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{J}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\text{Tr}_{s}\left\{ \widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right\} .\label{eq:polarization_mean}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
energy conservation
\end_layout

\end_inset

The total energy of the electronic system and the classical EM field is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}U_{\mathrm{tot}}\left(\widehat{\rho},\mathbf{E},\mathbf{B}\right) & =\mathrm{Tr}_{s}\left(\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{H}_{s}\right)+\\
 & \int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\left(\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)^{2}\right).
\end{split}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One of most important strengths is that the total energy is conserved (as
 can be shown easily).
 Furthermore, Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:liouville_rho"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:maxwell_EB"

\end_inset

 can be propagated in a concurrent manner.
 Therefore, Ehrenfest dynamics is a self-consistent, computationally inexpensive
 approach for propagating the electronic and EM field dynamics simultaneously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Drawback of Ehrenfest Dynamics: Spontaneous Emission
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, for the purpose of this paper, it will now be fruitful to
 spontaneous emission in more detail.
 In Ref.
