status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
onlinecite{li_mixed_2018}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it has been shown analytically and numerically that the decay rate predicted
 by Ehrenfest dynamics equals to the FGR rate multiplied by the instantaneous
 lower state population , i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{Eh}^{\text{1D}}\left(t\right)=\kappa^{\text{1D}}\rho_{00}\left(t\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for spontaneous emission of a two level system in a 1D space.
 Here we show the relation is generally valid for a 3D system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
what are the sources?
\end_layout

\end_inset

To prove the relation, we first need derive an analytical expression for
 the classical EM field.
 Consider the transition dipole moment of the two level system is polarized
 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction and the polarization distribution is a delta function at the
 origin,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\mu_{01}\delta\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\hat{\mathbf{z}}\left(\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|+\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Within Ehrenfest dynamics, the average polarization yields the bounded charge
 the average current
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & -\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\mathbf{P}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\\
\mathbf{J}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{P}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\equiv J\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\hat{\mathbf{z}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

as the sources for emanating classical EM fields.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
retarded potential
\end_layout

\end_inset

Given the sources are of the delta function form in a 3D space, we can write
 down the retarded potential expressed in the frequency domain
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "panofsky_classical_1962"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\phi_{\omega}^{\mathrm{ret}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right) & = & \frac{\rho_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}r}e^{i\omega r/c}\\
\mathbf{A}_{\omega}^{\mathrm{ret}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right) & = & \frac{\mu_{0}J_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)}{4\pi r}e^{i\omega r/c}\hat{\mathbf{z}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\omega}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\omega}$
\end_inset

 are the Fourier component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\int d\omega e^{-i\omega t}\rho_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\int d\omega e^{-i\omega t}J_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 We now can construct the retarded electric field in the frequency domain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\frac{e^{i\omega r/c}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\left(\frac{\rho_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)}{r^{2}}\hat{\mathbf{r}}-i\omega\frac{\rho_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)}{cr}\hat{\mathbf{r}}+i\omega\frac{J_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)}{c^{2}r}\hat{\mathbf{z}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which takes a similar form as Jefimenko's equations.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "panofsky_classical_1962"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
P.E
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we can also write the matrix element of the dipole coupling in electronic
 Hamiltonian Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:electronic_Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}=-\int d\mathbf{r}\mu_{01}\delta\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\hat{\mathbf{z}}\cdot\int d\omega e^{-i\omega t}\mathbf{E}_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here we find that the first two terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{z}}\cdot\mathbf{E}_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 vanishes for the integration.
 According to the transverse projection operator, we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}J_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\hat{\mathbf{z}}$
\end_inset

 for the the transverse component.
 Then we can use 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{J}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\int d\omega\left(-\omega^{2}\right)e^{-i\omega t}J_{\omega}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{01}^{\mathrm{el}}=\frac{\mu_{01}\ddot{J}\left(0,t\right)}{6\pi\epsilon_{0}c^{3}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since we are limited in the FGR regime, 
\begin_inset Formula $J\left(0,t\right)=-2\omega_{0}\mu_{01}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\left(t\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\left(t\right)\right]\approx\sqrt{\rho_{00}\rho_{11}}\sin\omega_{0}t$
\end_inset

, we can further approximate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{01}^{el}\approx-\frac{\omega_{0}^{3}\mu_{01}^{2}}{3\pi\epsilon_{0}c^{3}}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\left(t\right)\right]=\hbar\kappa^{\text{3D}}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\left(t\right)\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Liouville equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we convert the Liouville equation, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:liouville_rho"

\end_inset

, depending parametrically on the classcial EM field to non-linear differential
 equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial\rho_{11}}{\partial t} & = & -2\kappa^{\text{3D}}\mathrm{Im}\left[\rho_{01}\right]^{2},\label{eq:rho_11-1}\\
\frac{\partial\rho_{01}}{\partial t} & = & i\omega_{0}\rho_{01}-i\kappa^{\text{3D}}\mathrm{Im}\rho_{01}\left(\rho_{11}-\rho_{00}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which depends only on the density matrix.
 Using the same approximation as above, the coherence can be written as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{01}\approx\left|\rho_{01}\right|e^{i\omega_{0}t}$
\end_inset

 for a short time scale and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\rho_{01}\right|^{2}=\rho_{00}\rho_{11}$
\end_inset

