\begin_inset Formula $C_{0,\mathbf{k}}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The retarded Green's operators are 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal G}\left(\varepsilon\right)=\left[\varepsilon-{\cal H}+i\eta\right]^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for the full Hamiltonian and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal G}_{0}\left(\varepsilon\right)=\left[\varepsilon-{\cal H}_{0}+i\eta\right]^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for the unperturbed Hamiltonian where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is a positive small quantity (
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow0^{+}$
\end_inset

).
 Using the Dyson's identity 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal G}={\cal G}_{0}+{\cal G}_{0}{\cal V}{\cal G}={\cal G}_{0}+{\cal G}{\cal V}{\cal G}_{0}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the retarded Green's function in a self-consistent expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal G}_{11}\left(\varepsilon\right) & = & \frac{1}{\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{1}+i\eta+\frac{i}{2}\Gamma\left(\varepsilon\right)},\\
{\cal G}_{\mathbf{k}1}\left(\varepsilon\right) & = & \frac{V_{\mathbf{k}}}{\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{0}-\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}+i\eta}\frac{1}{\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{1}+i\eta+\frac{i}{2}\Gamma\left(\varepsilon\right)},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the self energy is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(\varepsilon\right)=2i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\left|V_{\mathbf{k}}\right|^{2}/\left(\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{0}-\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}+i\eta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The self energy can be evaluated by Cauchy integral identity (ignore the
 principle value part).
 For 1D, we consider a dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{01}$
\end_inset

 and use the density of states of a 1D system to obtain the self energy
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma^{\text{1D}}\left(\varepsilon\right) & = & 2i\frac{L}{2\pi}\int dk\frac{\mu_{01}^{2}\mathcal{E}_{k}^{2}}{\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{0}-\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}+i\eta}\\
 & = & i\frac{\mu_{01}^{2}}{2\pi\epsilon_{0}\hbar c}\left[-i\pi\left(\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{0}\right)\right]\\
 & = & \frac{\mu_{01}^{2}}{\epsilon_{0}\hbar c}\left(\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{0}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For 3D, we consider the dipole moment is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{01}=\mu_{01}\hat{\mathbf{z}}$
\end_inset

